## Context
Ticket 0026 defines three lexical methods that provide an independent
signal from embeddings. These operate on raw abstract text.

Reads: refined_works.csv (abstract column)
Writes: content/tables/tab_lexical_divergence.csv

## Actions
1. Create `scripts/compute_divergence_lexical.py` following script-io
   discipline.
2. Implement three methods:
   - L1: JS divergence on TF-IDF distributions between consecutive windows.
     Use scipy.spatial.distance.jensenshannon on vocabulary vectors.
   - L2: Novelty/Transience (Barron et al. 2018). For each document,
     KL(doc || past_w) and KL(doc || future_w) using TF-IDF representations.
     Aggregate per year: mean novelty, mean transience, mean resonance.
     Windows: 3, 5 years.
   - L3: Burst detection (Kleinberg via pybursts). Run on top-200 terms
     by corpus frequency. Aggregate: count of terms in burst state per year.
3. Parameter sweep: windows = [2, 3, 4, 5] for L1; past/future = [3, 5]
   for L2; default params for L3.
4. Subcorpus: full and core-only.
5. Output: long-format CSV matching 0029 schema.
6. Add Makefile target.

## Test
```python
def test_lexical_divergence_smoke():
    """Run L1-L3 on smoke fixture, verify output shape."""
```

## Exit criteria
Script runs on full corpus in < 10 minutes (TF-IDF vectorization is the
bottleneck). L1 and L2 produce smooth series. L3 produces integer counts.
